An abnormal configuration of the lower lip such that it is turned outward i.e., everted, with the Inner aspect of the lower lip vermilion (normally opposing the teeth) being visible in a frontal view.

Abnormally lax eyelid associated with tissue relaxation, predominantly in the vertical plane. It can be demonstrated by vertical lid pull. Loosening of vertical stabilising structures (e.g. lower lid retractors) or tarsal atrophy are often present.
A gap in the upper lip. This is a congenital defect resulting from nonfusion of tissues of the lip during embryonal development.
Presence of only 10 (instead of the usual 12) pairs of ribs.

Neonatal bilateral symmetric tonic seizure is a type of neonatal electro-clinical tonic seizure where the sustained increase in muscle tone, lasting a few seconds to minutes, occurs at both sides of the body symmetrically.
EEG with repetitive generalized sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.
The loss of gum tissue. The result is that gum tissue is recessed and its position on the tooth is lowered, exposing the roots of the teeth.
Hypsarrhythmia occurring in one hemisphere.
Posterior displacement of the tongue into the pharynx, i.e., a tongue that is mislocalised posteriorly.

Tubular cross section with intracytoplasmic vacuoles in at least one tubular epithelial cell. This feature is classified as isometric when vacuoles are round and similar in size and coarse when vacuoles were not round in shape or varied in size.
A deviation from normal signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia.
A darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter.
An abnormality of morphology of molar tooth.
The ring may be completed by the ductal ligament.

Periglomerular fibrosis is defined as glomeruli with open capillaries, but lamellated, frequently wrinkled, Bowman capsular basement membrane and circumferential layers of interstitial-type collagen around, within, or between the usually thickened, frequently lamellated, Bowman capsule basement membrane.
Developmental hypoplasia of the eyelid.
A developmental defect characterized by lack of a soft palate.
Increased pigmentation, either focal or generalized, of the mucosa of the mouth.
Narrowing of the urethra associated with inflammation or scar tissue.

A type of bicuspid aortic valve (BAV) characterized by a single raphe between the left and noncoronary cusps (LN fusion pattern). There is thus one completely developed right cusp, two completely developed commissures, and one raphe between the underdeveloped left and noncoronary coronary cusps extending to the corresponding malformed commissure.
Misaligned incisor.
Decreased amount of pigmentation in the fovea centralis.
An abnormal anteroposterior extension of the maxillary teeth beyond the plane of the mandibular teeth upon jaw closure.
Inflammatory or noninflammatory diseases affecting the glomeruli of the nephron.

Asymmetric neonatal electro-clinical sequential motor seizure is a type of neonatal electro-clinical seizure where the predominant feature cannot be detected because of seizures presenting asymmetrically with a variety of clinical and electrographic signs, often changing lateralization within or between seizures.
Increased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD above mean for age. Alternatively, an apparently increased maximum width of the tooth.
A count of antral follicles that is lower than normal for age.

The frontozygomatic or Number 8 cleft is found in both Treacher Collins syndrome and the Goldenhar variant of hemifacial microsomia. Skeletal defects are more prominent in Treacher Collins syndrome, whereas the soft tissue clefting is more typical in cases of ''Goldenhar syndrome''. Soft tissue clefting presents as a dermatocele, a true lateral eyelid coloboma with absence of the outer canthus, and anomalies of the globe itself, especially epibulbar cysts in patients with Goldenhar syndrome. The frontozygomatic bony cleft produces absence of the lateral orbital rim; this border now is formed by the hypoplastic greater wing of the sphenoid. The absence of bony support for the outer canthus produces lateral canthal dystopia and the characteristic antimongoloid slant of the palpebral fissures. Secondary to the bony deficiency in the lateral orbital wall and floor, there is soft tissue continuity between the orbit, temporal fossa, and infratemporal region. Preauricular hairline indicators delineate the Number 8 cleft as the first of the northbound clefts. Complete absence of the bony lateral orbital wall and rim constitute the skeletal element of the Number 8 cleft. The lateral border of the orbit is formed by the greater wing of the sphenoid from which small spicules of bone, which represent the rudimentary zygoma, may be found in Treacher Collins syndrome. The symmetry of the facial anomalies is reflected in the apparently normal symmetric anterior and middle cranial fossae.
Reduced size of the superior frontal portion of the cerebral cortex.
Increased width of the upper lip.
Underdevelopment of the fovea centralis.
A type of nuclear cataract involving congenital dust-like (pulverulent) opacity of the embryonal and fetal nucleus.
A subjective feeling that an experience which is occurring for the first time has been experienced before.
A herniation of meninges through a congenital bone defect in the skull in the parietal region.
An eccentric abnormal localized widening (dilatation) of the ascending tubular aorta that involves only a portion of the circumference of the vessel wall.
Lightening or darkening of the lips from their usual coloring.
Absence of urine, clinically classified as below 50ml/day.
A type of pigment gallstone that is brown, containing calcium fatty acids. These stones are softer than black pigment gallstones.

Exotropia (intermittent or constant) on distance fixation with binocular single vision on near fixation under all testing conditions. The accommodative convergence/accommodation (AC:A) ratio is within normal limits.
Having a characteristic appearance of a slate gray area of pigmentation within the disc margins that commonly appears along the inferotemporal or temporal neuroretinal rim areas.
A defect of development of the brain characterized by replacement of greater portions of the cerebral hemispheres and the corpus striatum by cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and glial tissue.
Constant exotropia for near and distance, presenting after 6 months of age.
Absent eyelids.
Infiltration of viruses into renal tubulointerstitial tissues as demonstrated on renal biopsy by viral inclusions which can be seen on routine stains or with immunohistochemistry.
Death of cells in the basal ganglia.
Underdevelopment of the lacrimal puncta.
An abnormality of the cerebral cortex with fewer gyri but with normal cortical thickness. This pattern is usually often associated with congenital microcephaly.
The malignant epithelial neoplasm with papillary growths in the nasolacrimal sac.

Neonatal seizure with bilateral asymmetric automatism is a type of neonatal electro-clinical seizure where the electrographic event is correlated with a coordinated motor activity, typically oral, usually with impaired awarness, occurring at both sides of the body symmetrically.

Cryptophthalmos is a condition of total absence of eyelids and the skin of forehead is continuous with that of cheek, in which the eyeball is completely concealed by the skin, which is stretched over the orbital cavity.
Chorioretinal atrophy concentrated around the optic papilla (i.e., the optic nerve head).
Protrusion of the arachnoid and dura through spinal foramina.
Abnormally lax lower eyelid associated with tissue relaxation.
Underdevelopment of the cerebellum.

Fusion of cervical vertebrae at C2 and C3, caused by a failure in the normal segmentation or division of the cervical vertebrae during the early weeks of fetal development, leading to a short neck with a low hairline at the back of the head, and restricted mobility of the upper spine.
Inflammation of the inner lining of the uterus (endometrium).
Accentuation of the grooves on the dorsal surface of the tongue.
Lack of development of the cerebellum.
An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth.
An abnormality of the globus pallidus.

Complexes of spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms), which are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy, in cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).
Structural abnormality of the basal ganglia related to defective development.
Presence of only 11 pairs of ribs.
A tongue-like protusion from the anterior aspect of lumbar vertebral bodies.
An elevation above the normal concentration of the HDL2b subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2b particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 9.7-12 nm.

Arnold-Chiari malformation consists of a downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils and the medulla through the foramen magnum, sometimes causing hydrocephalus as a result of obstruction of CSF outflow.
Neonatal unilateral epileptic spasm is a sudden flexion, extension, or mixed extension-flexion of predominantly proximal and truncal muscles that occurs at one side of the body.
A type of pigment gallstone that is hard and black, containing calcium carbonate and calcium phosphates.
A vascular malformation located in the lip that is related to abnormal vascular morphogenesis.
Reduced size of the cerebellar cortex.
An elevation above the normal concentration of the HDL2a subfraction in the blood circulation. An HDL2A particle is defined as an HDL particle with a size of 8.80-9.69 nm.
An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.
The closed form of spina bifida with incomplete closure of the vertebra L5 with intact overlying skin.
A dental anomaly characterized by the presence of a two fused teeth.

A progressive detrimental connective tissue deposition (fibrosis) on the kidney parenchyma involving the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney. Tubulointerstitial injury in the kidney is complex, involving a number of independent and overlapping cellular and molecular pathways, with renal interstitial fibrosis and tubular atrophy (IF/TA) as the final common pathway. However, IF and TA are separable, as shown by the profound TA in renal artery stenosis, which characteristically has little or no fibrosis (or inflammation). For new annotations it is preferable to annotate to the specific HPO terms for Renal interstitial lfibrosis and/or Renal tubular atrophy.
A type of urethral stricture affecting the pendulous urethra, which is straight and fixed to the corpora cavernosa.
Gentle upward curve of the upper lip vermilion such that the center is placed well superior to the commissures.
Periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs)are periodic, lateralized, and epileptiform. PLEDs show a relatively constant interval between discharges (0.5 to 3 seconds).
EEG with sharp waves in the parietal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
Segmental accumulation of scar tissue in individual (but not all) glomeruli.
A structural anomaly of the inferior portion of the vermis of cerebellum.
The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, the inclination of the palpebral fissure is greater than typical for age.

The presence, on T2-weighted magnetic resonance imaging, of markedly low signal intensity if the globus pallidus that surrounds a central region of high signal intensity in the anteromedial globus pallidus, producing an eye-of-the-tiger appearance.
Tubulointerstitial infiltration of bacteria identified on routine and/or special (Brown-Hopps) stains.
Increased width of the uvula (subjective finding).
Decreased length and width of the tongue.
Decreased size of the primary teeth.
A subtle unilateral cleft of the upper lip, which may appear as a small indentation.
Complete and diffuse scarring of glomerulus.
Incisors with a thick marginal ridge surrounding a deep lingual fossa are termed shovel-shaped incisors.
A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures.
Abnormal growth of endometrial cells (which are normally limited to the uterus) within the cervix.
Underdeveloped pedicle of the fifth lumbar vertebra.

Widening of the wall of capillary blood vessels in the glomerulus. This feature may be produced by deposits and other changes affecting either subepithelial and subendothelial regions or the glomerular basement membrane itself.
Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar.
Any structural anomaly of the putamen, a brain nucleus which together with the caudate nucleus and fundus striati makes up the striatum.

Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.
Delayed tooth eruption affecting the secondary dentition.
A green staining of teeth.
A type of renal tubular atrophy characterized by endocrine-like appearance of tubules, which are small and have narrow lumina, clear cells, and relatively thin basement membranes.

Polymicrogyria (an excessive number of small gyri or convolutions) that is maximal in perisylvian regions (the regions that surround the Sylvian fissures), which may be symmetric or asymmetric and may extend beyond perisylvian regions. The Sylvian fissures often extend posteriorly and superiorly.
The presence of discolored lateral incisors.
Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in one hemisphere.
Diffuse sclerosis of the mesangium, as manifestated by diffuse mesangial matrix expansion.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the central region.
A short discontinuity of the margin of the upper eyelid.
The presence of a V-shaped indentation (notch) in the primary central incisor.
Decreased size of the maxillary permanent incisor.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the temporal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Symmetric generalized polymicrogyria with no obvious gradient or region of maximal severity; may have abnormal high signal in white matter.
Cleft palate of the midline of the palate.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the frontal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Dissolution or attenuation of mesangial matrix and degeneration of mesangial cells. In essence, mesangiolysis is an injurious process which affects the glomerular mesangium without causing obvious damage to the capillary basement membranes. The matrix swells, loosens, and eventually dissolves; the mesangial cells may show only edema and vacuolization, or may undergo severe degeneration and necrosis.
Underdevelopment of the anterior commissure.
Underdevelopment of the cerebral white matter.
EEG with sharp waves in the central region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
A type of polymicrogyria with a gradient of severity (anterior more severe than posterior) extending from frontal poles posteriorly to precentral gyrus and inferiorly to frontal operculum.
Developmental hypoplasia of the tooth germ, i.e., of the structure that forms in odontogenesis that will develop into a tooth.

Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Areas of white discoloration visible on the surface of the teeth (enamel) in the form of streaks or specks.
The presence of complexes of slow spikes and slow waves (<2.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).
Neurodegeneration involving the globus pallidus,a part of the basal ganglia that is involved in the regulation of voluntary movement.
Atrophy of the occipital cortex.
The presence of complexes of repetitive spikes and waves in EEG.
EEG with sharp waves in the occipital region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
An abnormality of morphology of permanent molar.
Lack of tooth eruption of the secondary dentition.
A diminished volume of the central part of the bed nucleus of the stria terminalis.
Increased depth of the median tongue furrow.
The union of two separately developing tooth germs typically leading to one less tooth than normal in the affected dental arch.
Absence of the anterior commissure.

Pachygyria is a malformation of cortical development with abnormally wide gyri with sulci 1,5-3 cm apart and abnormally thick cortex measuring more than 5 mm (radiological definition). See also neuropathological definitions for 2-, 3-, and 4-layered lissencephaly.
Epileptiform discharges being identified at multiple locations in both hemispheres.
A type of renal tubular atrophy in which the tubules show thick tubular basement membranes lined by small cuboidal or flat cells. Generally accompanied by fibrosis.
The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations below the mean.
Periodically recurring abnormalities in the EEG.
The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (2.5-3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).
Flat skin surface, with no ridge formation in the central region of the upper lip between the nasal base and upper vermilion border.
An abnormal area of increased brightness (hyperintensity) that occurs in several distinct areas.
Hypointence (dark) appearance of the substantia nigra inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).
Increase in size of the podocytes of the renal glomerulus.
Congenital defect with failure of the development of the cerebral white matter.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the central region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Excessive number of small gyri (convolutions) on the surface of one side of the brain.
Defective development of the vermis of cerebellum.
Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.
The presence of complexes of spikes and waves (>3.5 Hz) in electroencephalography (EEG).
A unilateral or bilateral eyelid retraction due to midbrain lesions.

A congenital abnormality of the cerebral hemisphere characterized by lack of gyrations (convolutions) of the cerebral cortex. Agyria is defined as cortical regions lacking gyration with sulci great than 3 cm apart and cerebral cortex thicker than 5 mm.
Narrowing of a tear duct (lacrimal duct).
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by abnormal cortical layering.
Underdevelopment or absence of the uvula.
A lighter than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hyperintensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.
A developmental anomaly characterized by a reduced number of teeth, whereby up to 6 teeth are missing.
The congenital absence of all teeth.
Accentuated, prominent philtral ridges giving rise to an exaggerated groove in the midline between the nasal base and upper vermillion border.
Hypointence (dark) appearance of the globus pallidus inmagnetic resonance imaging using susceptibility weighted imaging (SWI).
Focal proliferation of glial cells in the substantia nigra.
An abnormal area of increased brightness (hyperintensity) that is limited to one particular area.
Acute inflammation of the kidney affecting the interstitium of the kidneys surrounding the tubules.
Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the deep cerebral white matter.
A very common condition in which the extreme end of the nasolacrimal duct underneath the inferior turbinate fails to complete its canalization in the newborn period.
A generalized form of microdontia.
Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from locations distant from the ventricular system.
Height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the midline more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently reduced height of the vermilion of the upper lip in the frontal view (subjective).
Increased space between the primary teeth. Note this phenotype should be distinguished from increased space due purely to microdontia.
Pathological deposition of calcium salts in the globus pallidus.
Inner aspect of the upper lip vermilion (normally apposing the teeth) visible in a frontal view, i.e., the presence of an everted upper lip.
Multiple punctate calcifications in the dental pulp.
A congenital defect characterized by the absence of one or more permanent teeth, including oligodontia, hypodontia, and adontia of the of permanent teeth.
A cleft of the lip with overlying mucous membrane.
An abnormality of morphology of the incisor tooth in which the tooth is shaped like a screwdriver blade, i.e., having a rhomboid shape.
Decreased width of the uvula.
Location of the urethral opening on the inferior aspect of the penis.
Developmental hypoplasia of the primary teeth.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the middle of the inferior shaft of the penis.
Dagger-shaped calcifications in the dental pulp.
Any structural abnormality of the caudate nucleus.
A type of malocclusion in which there is a gap between the anterior teeth (incisors).
Increased numbers of mesangial cells per glomerulus, defined as four or more nuclei in a peripheral mesangial segment.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the parietal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by disrupted cortical lamination and specific cytological abnormalities.
The presence of a single, median maxillary incisor, affecting both the primary maxillary incisor and the permanent maxillary incisor.
Erupted tooth or teeth at birth.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the occipital region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Distance between medial and lateral canthi is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, apparently increased length of the palpebral fissures.

Dysplasia and dysgenesis of the corpus callosum are nonspecific descriptions that imply defective development of the corpus callosum. The term dysplasia is applied when the morphology of the corpus callosum is altered as a congenital trait. For instance, the corpus callosum may be hump-shaped, kinked, or a striped corpus callosum that lacks an anatomically distinct genu and splenium.
A tooth that has not erupted because of local impediments (overcrowding or fibrous gum overgrowth).
A congenital defect of development characterized by absence of the lacrimal gland.
Absence or underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
The upper incisors deviate from the normal angle of being roughly parallel to the surface of the face and instead slant outwards.

Atrophy of one side of the brain, characterized by findings including thinning of the cerebral cortex, reduced volume of the cerebral white matter with abnormal myelination, and enlargement of the ispilateral fourth ventricle.
A type of renal tubular atrophy characterized by a thyroid-like appearance, with small round tubules with markedly flattened, simplified epithelium and uniform intratubular casts.
Abnormally bright T2 signal from the striatum on brain magnetic resonance imaging.
More pronounced paramedian peaks and median notch of the Cupid's bow.
A congenital absence of the convolutions of the cerebral cortex and a poorly formed sylvian fissure that affects a particular part of the cortex.
EEG with sharp waves in the temporal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
The presence of multiple embedded tooth germs which have failed to erupt.
Increased length of the uvula.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the perineal region.
Wasting (atrophy) of the vermis of cerebellum.
An abnormal build up of iron (Fe) in the globus pallidus.
Renal tubulointerstitial infiltration of mycobacteria identified on acid-fast or Fite stains. Can be associated with granulomatous inflammation.
An anomaly of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
An abnormality of the incisor characterized by invagination of the enamel, giving a radiographic appearance that suggests a tooth within a tooth.
Absence of the tongue owing to a developmental abnormality.
Soft and hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the soft and hard palate that are covered by the lining (ie mucous membrane) of the roof of the mouth.
A developmental anomaly characterized by a reduced number of teeth, whereby more than 6 teeth are missing.
The presence of a supernumerary, i.e., extra, maxillary incisor, either the primary maxillary incisor or the permanent maxillary incisor.
An anomalous build up of iron (Fe) in the substantia nigra.

Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border.
An alteration of the color of the lip to take on a violet color. This term does not include cyanosis.
Atrophy of the frontal cortex.
Clefting of the upper lip affecting the lateral portions of the upper lip rather than the midline/median region.
A benign tumor composed of adipose tissue and dense connective tissue usually located near the temporal fornix.
Talon cusp is an accessory cusp located near the cingulum (the portion of the lingual or palatal aspect of the tooth that forms a convex protuberance at the cervical third of the anatomic crown).

A developmental disorder characterized by the progressive loss of primordial germ cells in the developing ovaries of an embryo, leading to hypoplastic ovaries composed of wavy connective tissue with occasional clumps of granulosa cells, and frequently mesonephric or hilar cells.
The presence of immunoglobulin A deposits in the glomerulus.
Hypospadias with location of the urethral meatus in the scrotum.
A type of dental misalignment with crowded central incisors, i.e., of maxillary secondary incisor, or of maxillary central primary incisor.
Chronic inflammation of the kidney affecting the interstitium of the kidneys surrounding the tubules.
Loss of pigment in the fovea centralis.
A type of focal cortical dysplasia that is characterized by cortical lamination abnormalities associated with a principal lesion, usually adjacent to or affecting the same cortical area/lobe.
The presence of atrophy (wasting) of the corpus callosum.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the central region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

A form of subcortical heterotopia with mislocalized gray matter within the white matter.It is defined as longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter. It is part of the lissencephaly spectrum.
Multiple areas of darker than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the cerebral ventricles.

Distance between the philtral ridges, measured just above the vermilion border, more than 2 standard deviations below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between the ridges of the philtrum.
Narrow ridge in the midline of the philtral groove.
Triangular appearance of the oral aperture with the apex in the midpoint of the upper vermilion and the lower vermilion forming the base.
Premature tooth eruption of the permanent dentition.
Lack of paramedian peaks and median notch of the upper lip vermilion.

Pachygyria-agyria spectrum whereby at neuropathological examination the cortical plate consists of a two-three layered organization made up of a molecular layer, a relatively thin wavy layer with a higher cellular density and a third layer with lower cellularity.
Underdevelopment of the lower eyelid.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the occipital region.
EEG shows spikes (<80 ms) and waves, which are recorded over the entire scalp and do not have a specific frequency.
An abnormality of the morphology of secondary premolar tooth.

A type of spinal dysraphism presenting as a subcutaneous fatty mass, that is, a spinal defect associated with lipomatous tissue, and covered by skin. The most usual location for lipomyelomeningocele is at the gluteal cleft.

Arnold-Chiari type I malformation refers to a relatively mild degree of herniation of the posteroinferior region of the cerebellum (the cerebellar tonsils) into the cervical canal with little or no displacement of the fourth ventricle.
Underdevelopment of the lacrimal gland.
Increased size of the incisor tooth.

A nasolacrimal duct obstruction presenting as a grey-blue cystic swelling just below the medial canthus. Believed to be a result of concomitant upper obstruction of the Rosenmuller valve and lower obstruction of the Hasner valve.
Areas of brighter than expected MRI signal in the white matter of the brain whereby individual patches run together.

Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency.

An anomaly of podocyte morphology characterized by the loss of the interdigitating foot process pattern (generally called foot process effacement; FPE). The term FPE designates the loss of the usual interdigitating pattern of foot processes of neighboring podocytes, leading to relatively broad expanses of podocyte processes covering the glomerular basement membrane (GBM). It is widely viewed as a pathological derangement that is associated with leakage of macromolecules such as albumin through the glomerular filtration barrier.
The presence of a supernumerary tooth in the midline between the maxillary central incisors.
A mild form of hypospadias in which the urethra opens just under the corona glandis.
A form of lissencephaly characterized by an uneven cortical surface with a so called 'cobblestone' appearace. There are no distinguishable cortical layers.
An excessive number of small gyri (convolutions) on the surface of the brain in the frontoparietal region.
Hypoplasia of the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus.
Electron dense deposits at the glomerular basement membrane,

A type of lissencephaly whereby upon neuropathological examination the cortical plate is severely disorganized with a festooned-like pattern and with neither lamination nor clear demarcation between white and grey matter.
The presence of complement 3 deposits in the glomerulus.
Polymicrogyria affecting one or multiple small areas of the cerebral cortex.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a diffuse hypointensity affecting all of the basal ganglia.
Delayed tooth eruption affecting the primary dentition.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the temporal region.
Increased size and molar morphology of premolar tooth.
Absence of the usual parallel position of philtral ridges.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the frontal region.
An abnormality of morphology of primary molar.
Polymicrogyria in parasagittal and mesial aspects of parieto-occipital cortex.
EEG with sharp slow waves in the frontal region. Sharp slow waves are focal sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec followed by a slow wave.
Pit in the midline of the philtral groove.
A darker than expected T2 signal on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the basal ganglia. This term refers to a localized hypointensity affecting a particular region of the basal ganglia.
Mulberry molars are irregular teeth generally affecting the first molars and are characterized by a grossly deformed crown imitating, as the name implies, the surface of a mulberry.
Tubulointerstitial infiltration of yeast or hyphal-microrganisms identified on routine and/or special (PAS, silver) stains.
Obliteration of the pulp chambers owing to mineralization of the dental pulp.
An abnormal conical morphology of the incisor tooth.
A type of urethral stricture affecting the bulbar urethra, which is the part of the urethra that traverses the root of the penis.
A type of cleft lip presenting as a midline (median) gap in the upper lip.
EEG with sharp waves in the frontal region, i.e., sharp transient waves of a duration between 80 and 200 msec.
Prominence of a triangular soft tissue area of the philtrum with the apex to the columella.
The severe form of a neural tube defect where the open neural tube appears as a flattened, plate-like mass of nervous tissue with no overlying membrane.
The development of two teeth from a single tooth bud, leading to a larger fused tooth.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec in the parietal region.

Centrally located corpus callosum hyperintensities said to resemble snowballs upon magnetic resonance imaging (with T2 or Sagittal fluid attenuated inversion recovery [FLAIR] sequences). The central location in the callosum makes them pathognomonic for Susac syndrome.
Narrowing (becoming gradually narrower) of the distance between lumbar vertebral pedicles that gets progressively more severe towards to caudal (lower) end of the vertebral column.
Underdevelopment of the philtrum.
A mass of granulation tissue in response to chronic dacryocystitis as polypoid formations or they follow accidental injury, from probing and as a reaction to retained foreign bodies in the sac.
Atrophy of the temporal cortex.
Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.
A short discontinuity of the margin of the lower eyelid.
A severe form of hypospadias in which the urethral opening is located at the junction of the penis and scrotum.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the temporal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Distance between the philtral ridges, measured just above the vermilion border, more than 2 standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased distance between the ridges of the philtrum.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the centrotemporal region of the brain (also known as the central sulcus), i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.
A type of urethral stricture affecting the fossa navicularis, which is the spongy part of the male urethra located at the glans penis.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the occipital region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

A form of lissencephaly in which the cortex is thickened and has four more or less disorganized layers rather than six normal layers resulting from incomplete neuronal migration during brain development. At neuropathological examination, a 4-layered cortex consists of an upper molecular layer, a second thin cellular layer containing pyramidal neurons usually observed in layer V, a third pale poorly cellular layer and a fourth thick deep layer made up of neurons which had failed to migrate. Radiologocally would manifest as agyria or pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm.
Reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids.
Reddish, brown opalescent discoloration of teeth in normal light.
Increased vertical dimension of the corpus callosum. This feature can be visualized by sagittal sections on magnetic resonance tomography imaging of the brain.
Distance between the medial and lateral canthi is more than 2 SD below the mean for age (objective); or, apparently reduced length of the palpebral fissures.

A shape created by an acute downward arching of the upper eyelid and upward arching of the lower eyelid, toward the medial canthus, which gives the outline of the palpebral fissures the configuration of an almond. Thus, the maximum distance between the fissures is offset from, and medial to, the center point.
Epileptiform discharges identified at multiple locations temporarily in both hemispheres and temporarily in one hemisphere.
Atrophy of the parietal cortex.
Focal spikes occurring for several seconds.
EEG with focal sharp transient waves in the parietal region, i.e., focal sharp waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

Severe microcephaly and lissencephaly with granular surfaces with immature cortical plate, reduced in thickness, with focal polymicrogyria and immature small neurons with rare processes, intermingled with a considerable number of glial elements.
A developmental defect characterized by the absence of the putamen owing to its failure to develop.

Areas of brighter than expected signal on magnetic resonance imaging emanating from the cerebral white matter that surrounds the fourth cerebral ventricle (which is located beneath the tentorium of the cerebellum).
An elevated concentration of lactate in the caudate nucleus. This finding can be elicited by magnetic resonance spectroscopy imaging.
Congenital absence of the vermis of cerebellum.
Underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum.
Underdevelopment of the corpus callosum.
Multiple pointlike areas of high T2 signal observed upon magnetic resonance imaging of the periventricular cerebral white matter.
Peg-shaped upper lateral secondary incisor tooth.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal tangential cortical lamination.

A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by altered architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia without six-layered structure) and/or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons) of the neocortex, which occur adjacent to glial or glioneuronal tumor.
Pachygyria with a mildly thickend cerebral cortex measuring 5-10 mm. Note that cortical thickness cannot be measured reliably on scans done between 3 and 24 months of age.
A cleft of the muscular (soft) portion of the palate that is covered by mucous membrane. Soft-palate submucous clefts are characterized by a midline deficiency or lack of muscle tissue.
A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures on one side only.

A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by altered architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia without six-layered structure) or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons) of the neocortex, which occur adjacent to other lesions acquired during early life (not included into FCD Type IIIa-c). These lesions comprise a large spectrum including traumatic brain injury, glial scarring after prenatal or perinatal ischemic injury or bleeding, and inflammatory or infectious diseases, i.e. Rasmussen encephalitis, limbic encephalitis, bacterial or viral infections.

Hard-palate submucous clefts are characterized by bony defects in the midline of the bony palate that are covered by the mucous membrane of the roof of the mouth. It may be possible to detect a submucous cleft hard palate upon palpation as a notch in the bony palate.

A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by alterations in architectural organisation (cortical dyslamination) or cytoarchitectural composition (hypertrophic neurons outside Layer 5) in patients with hippocampal sclerosis (HS, syn. Ammon's horn sclerosis).
Agenesis of canine tooth.
Congenital absence of a part of the vermis of cerebellum.
Periodically occurring generalized periodic complexes.
Increased width of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal radial cortical lamination.
Lack of the uvula.

A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type III that is characterized by alterations in architectural (cortical dyslamination, hypoplasia) or cytoarchitectural composition of the neocortex (hypertrophic neurons), which occur adjacent to vascular malformations (cavernomas, arteriovenous malformations, leptomeningeal vascular malformations, telangiectasias, meningioangiomatosis).
Decreased length of the uvula.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type II that is characterized by dysmorphic neurons (significantly enlarged with accumulation of neurofilament proteins) and balloon cells.

A gap (cleft) affecting one of the alveolar ridges, which are the protuberances in the mouth that contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth. An alveolar cleft can affect all structures of the alveolar ridge, including the gingiva, other mucosa, periosteum, alveolar bone, and teeth.
Agenesis of premolar tooth.

A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type II that is characterized by dysmorphic neurons, which present with a significantly enlarged cell body and nucleus, malorientation, abnormally distributed intracellular Nissl substance and cytoplasmic accumulation of neurofilament proteins.
Pachygyria with a very thick cerebral cortex measuring 10-20 mm. Note that cortical thickness cannot be measured reliably on scans done between 3 and 24 months of age.
Atrophy of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
Nonmidline cleft palate on the left and right sides.
Cleft lip or palate affecting the midline region of the palate.
Increased length of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that largely affects one side of the brain.
Agenesis of molar tooth.
Benign tumor of the nasolacrimal sac.
Increased size of the maxillary central secondary incisor tooth.
An abnormal conical morphology of either maxillary primary incisor tooth or maxillary permanent incisor tooth or both.

Absence of the corpus callosum as a result of the failure of the corpus callosum to develop, which can be the result of a failure in any one of the multiple steps of callosal development including cellular proliferation and migration, axonal growth or glial patterning at the midline.
A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on one side only.
Agenesis of incisor.
An abnormal conical morphology of the primary incisor.
Short dental root.
An abnormal conical morphology of the primary or permanent mandibular incisors.
Reduced number of primary teeth.
Increased volume of dental pulp of permanent molar.
Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the whole brain.
A non-midline cleft of the upper lip on the left and right sides.
The presence of multiple impacted teeth.
Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible along the occipital cortex.
A type of perisylvian polymicrogyria that affects both sides of the brain.
Abnormal splayed configuration (spreading out) of the superior cerebellar peduncle.
Longitudinal bands of gray matter located deep to the cerebral cortex and separated from it by a thin layer of normal appearing white matter visible in the frontal and temporal lobes.
Uvula separated into two parts most easily seen at the tip.

Pachygyria with cortical thickness above 10 mm with and a posterior predominant severety gradient. The severety gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Posterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.

Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and an anterior predominant severity gradient. The severety gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Anterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe over the frontal and temporal lobes.
Agenesis of secondary molar tooth.

Pachygyria with cortical thickness between 5 and 10 mm with and a posterior predominant severety gradient. The severety gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically over 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Posterior predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.
Nonmidline alveolar cleft of the maxilla.
Agenesis of mandibular premolar.
Increased distance between the maxillary central permanent incisor tooth.
Agenesis of maxillary premolar.
One sided alveolar cleft of the maxilla.
A subtype of focal cortical dysplasia type I that is characterized by abnormal radial and tangential cortical lamination.
Cleft lip and cleft palate affecting both sides of the face.

Pachygyria with cortical thickness greater than 10 mm and a perisylvian predominant severity gradient. The severity gradient is determined based on the gyral width, with gyri typically wider than 5mm over the more severely affected regions. Perisylvian predominant gradient indicates pachygyria more severe other the occipital lobes but also includes a rare perisylvian-predominant pachygyria and a temporal predominant pachygyria.
Agenesis of one or more central incisors, i.e., of lower secondary incisor, lower primary incisor, upper secondary incisor, or of upper central primary incisor.
A partial failure of the development of the corpus callosum.
Underdevelopment of the inferior portion of the vermis of cerebellum.
Agenesis of lower secondary incisor or lower primary incisor.
Agenesis of either maxillary first permanent molar or mandibular first permanent molar or both.
Agenesis of either mandibular second permanent molar or maxillary second permanent molar.
Agenesis of one or more maxillary lateral incisor, comprising the maxillary lateral primary incisor and maxillary lateral secondary incisor.
Agenesis of upper secondary incisor or of upper central primary incisor.
Agenesis of one or more maxillary lateral incisor, comprising the maxillary lateral primary incisor.
Agenesis of upper central primary incisor.
Agenesis of lower primary incisor.
Agenesis of upper secondary incisor.
Agenesis of lower secondary incisor.
Agenesis of one or more upper lateral secondary incisor.
